# VAK_4d — VAkK_4.64

## 1. Sanskrit — Devanāgarī

अशैक्षं कायवाक्कर्म मनश्चैव यथाक्रमम् ।
मौनत्रयं त्रिधा शौचं सर्वं सुचरितत्रयम् ॥ VAkK_4.64 ॥

## 2. Sanskrit — IAST

aśaikṣaṃ kāyavākkarma manaś caiva yathākramam /
maunatrayaṃ tridhā śaucaṃ sarvaṃ sucaritatrayam // VAkK_4.64 //

Source note: the reference text prints `sarva sucaritatrayam`; this first-pass file normalizes the expected neuter agreement as `sarvaṃ sucaritatrayam`. Recheck during the Bhāṣya/textual pass.

## 3. Padaccheda

| Sandhi form | Padaccheda | Basic meaning |
|---|---|---|
| aśaikṣam | a-śaikṣam | beyond training; belonging to the one beyond training |
| kāyavākkarma | kāya-vāk-karma | bodily and verbal karma |
| manaś caiva | manaḥ ca eva | and mind precisely |
| yathākramam | yathā-kramam | respectively; in the stated order |
| maunatrayam | mauna-trayam | the three silences |
| tridhā | tridhā | threefold; in three ways |
| śaucam | śaucam | purity |
| sarvam | sarvam | the whole; all of it |
| sucaritatrayam | sucarita-trayam | threefold good conduct |

Expanded construction:

```text
aśaikṣam kāya-karma
aśaikṣam vāk-karma
aśaikṣam manaḥ
ca eva
yathā-kramam

mauna-trayam

tridhā śaucam
sarvam sucarita-trayam
```

## 4. Grammar

- `aśaikṣam`: neuter nominative singular, used distributively across bodily karma, verbal karma, and mind.
- `kāya-vāk-karma`: neuter compound naming bodily and verbal action.
- `manaḥ`: neuter nominative singular of `manas`.
- `yathākramam`: indeclinable, “respectively.”
- `mauna-trayam`: neuter nominative singular, “the threefold silence.”
- `tridhā`: indeclinable, “threefold.”
- `śaucam`: neuter nominative singular, “purity.”
- `sarvam sucarita-trayam`: “the complete threefold good conduct.”

The first half correlates:

```text
aśaikṣa bodily karma
aśaikṣa verbal karma
aśaikṣa mind
```

with:

```text
bodily silence
verbal silence
mental silence
```

The second half identifies threefold purity with bodily, verbal, and mental good conduct as a whole.

## 5. Literal Translation

The bodily action, verbal action, and mind of one beyond training are, respectively, the threefold silence. Threefold purity is the entire threefold good conduct.

## 6. Philosophical Translation

Perfected bodily action, perfected speech, and the perfected mind constitute, respectively, silence of body, silence of speech, and silence of mind. Purity in its complete threefold form consists in good bodily, verbal, and mental conduct.

Silence here is not mere inactivity. It is activity freed from the necessity of further discipline.

```text
silence
    ≠ simple inactivity

silence
    = activity freed from further correction
```

## 7. Technical Vocabulary

### aśaikṣa

`aśaikṣa` means “beyond training,” not “untrained.” It names one for whom nothing further remains to be cultivated.

### kāya-karman / vāk-karman

Bodily and verbal action are called bodily and verbal silence when perfected in the aśaikṣa.

### manas

The third member is `manas`, not explicitly `mano-karma`. This asymmetry is important:

```text
bodily karma
verbal karma
mind
```

Mind may be named as the inward source from which bodily and verbal manifestation proceed.

### mauna

`mauna` is positive perfected activity, not muteness or inertness.

### śauca

`śauca` is purity or cleanliness. Here it comprises the entire threefold field of good conduct.

### sucarita

`su-carita` is good conduct or a well-conducted course of activity. The anticipated members are bodily, verbal, and mental good conduct.

## 8. Doctrinal Determination

The verse begins the analysis of karma through three domains:

```text
body
speech
mind
```

It determines this triple in two ways.

### Threefold silence

```text
aśaikṣa bodily action
aśaikṣa verbal action
aśaikṣa mind
        ↓
threefold silence
```

### Threefold purity

```text
bodily good conduct
verbal good conduct
mental good conduct
        ↓
threefold purity
```

Purity is broader than the perfected silence of the aśaikṣa. A trainee may possess good conduct while still requiring further cultivation.

Provisional relation:

```text
mauna
    special perfected form of
śauca
    expressed through
sucarita-traya
```

## 9. Logical Determination

The verse shifts from karma classified by result to karma classified by operative medium:

```text
body
speech
mind
```

The triple is the incarnation of the higher determination of purified conduct.

`mauna` is determinate negation:

```text
corrupt bodily activity negated within bodily activity
corrupt verbal activity negated within verbal activity
corrupt mental determination negated within mind
```

Thus:

```text
abstract silence
    = absence of manifestation

determinate silence
    = manifestation without defilement
```

The verse’s asymmetry remains significant:

```text
kāya-vāk-karma
manaḥ
```

Body and speech are named as externalized karma; mind is named as their inward source-determination.

## 10. Light Organon Interpretation

VAK_4.64 marks the movement:

```text
karma classified by result
        ↓
karma classified as conduct
```

The textual order is body, speech, mind. A possible genetic order is mind, speech, body, but the kārikā’s own order must be preserved in the primary analysis.

The central first-pass insight is:

```text
perfected karma
    becomes silence
```

This does not cancel Activity. It presents Activity whose law has become wholly immanent.

```text
unpurified karma
    = activity divided against its law

sucarita
    = activity conforming to its law

aśaikṣa-mauna
    = activity transparent to its determination
```

